Basic Definitions

Population

  • (Textbook) A population is the entire collection of individuals about which information is sought.

  • All possible outcomes in a chance experiment.

Sample

  • (Textbook) A sample is a subset of a population, containing the individuals that are actually observed.

  • A simple random sample of size n is a sample chosen by a method in which each collection of n population items is equally likely to make up the sample, just as in lottery.

Measures of Center (Mean and Median)

Sample Mean: It is denoted with the symbol \(\bar{X}\).

  • Computation: Add all values \((\sum x_i)\) and divided by the sample size (n).

  • Formula: \(\bar{X} = \frac{1}{n}\sum x_i\)

  • The average or typical value of your data is measured by the mean.

  • The population mean is denoted with the symbol \(\mu\) (read as mu).

  • The sample mean is denoted with the symbol \(\bar{X}\) (read as X-BAR).

Median: By definition, it is a number that splits the data set in half.

  • Step 1: Sort the data in ascending order.

  • Step 2: If the sample size is ODD, the median is the number in the middle position, else the median is the average of the two middle numbers.

Flight Time: The following data represent the flight time (in minutes) of a random sample of seven flights from Las Vegas, Nevada, to Newark, New Jersey, on United Airlines: 282, 270, 260, 266, 257, 260, 277.

Sample Mean: \(\bar{X} = \frac{1}{n}\sum X_i\)

  • \(\bar{X} = \frac{1}{7}(282 + 270 + 260 + 266 + 257 + 260 + 277)\)

  • \(\bar{X} = \frac{1}{7}(1872)\) = 267.43

Median = 266

  • Sort data: 257 260 260 266 270 277 282

  • Since the sample size is odd, 7, Median is the number in \(4^{th}\) position, 266

Mean vs Median vs Mode

Shape Relationship Best Summary of Center
Bell-Shaped mean = median = mode mean
Skewed Right mean > median > mode median
Skewed Left mean < median < mode median

  • The mode of a variable is the most frequent observation in the data set.

  • Be careful, the mode is not a measure of central tendency!!!

  • The mean (or median) can be interpreted as typical values or averages. We can also say that half of the data is below (or above) the median.

  • The best summary (mean or median) of the center depends on the shape of the variables distribution.

Mean for Grouped Data

The table below presents the number of text messages sent by a sample of 50 high school students. We will approximate the mean number of messages sent.

Messages sent Frequency
0 - 49 10
50 - 99 5
100 - 149 13
150 - 199 11
200 - 249 7
250 - 299 4

Procedures for Approximating the Mean with Grouped Data

Step 1: Compute the midpoint of each class.

The midpoint of a class is found by taking the average of the lower class limit and the lower limit of the next larger class. For the last class, there is no next larger class, but we use the lower limit that the next larger class would have.

Messages sent Frequency Midpoint
0 - 49 10 25
50 - 99 5 75
100 - 149 13 125
150 - 199 11 175
200 - 249 7 225
250 - 299 4 275

Step 2: For each class, multiply the class midpoint by the class frequency.

Messages sent Frequency Midpoint F x M
0 - 49 10 25 250
50 - 99 5 75 375
100 - 149 13 125 1625
150 - 199 11 175 1925
200 - 249 7 225 1575
250 - 299 4 275 1100

Step 3: Add the products (Midpoint x Frequency) over all classes.

Total of (F x M) = 250 + 375 + 1625 + 1925 + 1575 + 1100 = 6850

Step 4: Divide the sum obtained in Step 3 by the sum of the frequencies.

Mean \(\approx\) 6850 / 50 = 137

The Weighted Mean

Definition: If \(x_1, x_2, ...x_n\) are data values, and \(w_1, w_2, ..., w_n\) are weights, the weighted mean is

\(\bar{X}_w = \frac{w_1x_1 + w_2x_2 + ... + w_nx_n}{w_1 + w_2 + ... + w_n} = \frac{w_ix_i}{w_i}\)

Example: Last semester Joe took four courses. He got A is statistics (5 credits), a B in psychology (4 credits), a C in English (3 credits), and an A in music (2 credits). An A is worth 4 quality points, a B is worth 3 points and a C is worth 2 points. Compute Joes GPA.

  • The data values are the points for each grade: 4, 3, 2, and 4.

  • The weights are the number of credits: 5, 4, 3, 2.

  • The GPA is the weighted mean: \(\frac{5(4) + 4(3) + 3(2) + 2(4)}{5 + 4 + 3 + 2}\)

  • GPA = 3.29

Measures of Spread or Variability

Range: It is the difference between the maximum and the minimum values in your data.

Range = Max - Min

The sample variance: It is denoted with the symbol \(S^2\).

\(S^2 = \frac{1}{n - 1}\sum(x_i - \bar{X})^2\)

The sample standard deviation is the square root of the variance: \(S = \sqrt{S^2}\). Interpret the standard deviation as the average distance of all data values to the mean.

If the population is known, the population variance computed with the formula

\(\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{n}\sum(x_i - \mu)^2\).

The population standard deviation is \(\sigma\) (read as sigma).

Exercise. The following data represent the flight time (in minutes) of a random sample of seven flights from Las Vegas, Nevada, to Newark, New Jersey, on United Airlines:

282, 270, 260, 266, 257, 260, 267

Compute the spread (or variability) of flight time data.

  • It is possible to measure the spread of your data with the range, standard deviation and IQR.

  • By definition, the range is the difference between the maximum and minimum data values.

  • In this example, Range = 282 - 257 = 25 minutes.

Step 1: Before computing the variance, it is necessary to find the mean, \(\bar{X}\).

\(\bar{x}\) = \(\frac{282 + 270 + 260 + 266 + 257 + 260 + 267}{7}\) = \(\frac{1862}{7}\) = 266

Step 2: Compute the difference between the data values and the mean.

time \((x_i - \bar{x})\)
282 16
270 4
260 -6
266 0
257 -9
260 -6
267 1

Step 3: Square the differences obtained in column 2

time \((x_i - \bar{x})\) \((x_i - \bar{x})^2\)
282 16 256
270 4 16
260 -6 36
266 0 0
257 -9 81
260 -6 36
267 1 1

Step 4: Add the total in column 3

\(\sum (x_i - \bar{x})^2\) = 256 + 16 + 36 + 0 + 81 + 36 + 1 = 426

Step 5: Get the variance by dividing the total by (n-1) where n is the sample size.

  • Variance, \(S^2\) = \(\frac{426}{7 - 1}\) = 71 mins \(^2\)

  • Standard Deviation, S = \(\sqrt{S^2}\) = \(\sqrt{71}\) = 8.426 mins

Standard Deviation for Grouped Data.

Consider the following data table:


Messages sent Frequency
0 - 49 10
50 - 99 5
100 - 149 13
150 - 199 11
200 - 249 7
250 - 299 4

Find the midpoint of each class and compute the grouped mean like we demonstrated previously.

  • Grouped mean = 137
Messages sent Frequency Midpoint Mean
0 - 49 10 25 137
50 - 99 5 75 137
100 - 149 13 125 137
150 - 199 11 175 137
200 - 249 7 225 137
250 - 299 4 275 137

Compute (midpoint - Mean)

Messages sent Frequency Midpoint Mean Midpoint - Mean
0 - 49 10 25 137 -112
50 - 99 5 75 137 -62
100 - 149 13 125 137 -12
150 - 199 11 175 137 38
200 - 249 7 225 137 88
250 - 299 4 275 137 138

Compute \((Md - Mn)^2\) x Frequency

Messages sent Frequency Md - Mn (Md - Mn)\(^2\) x Frequency
0 - 49 10 -112 125400
50 - 99 5 -62 19200
100 - 149 13 -12 1872
150 - 199 11 38 15884
200 - 249 7 88 54208
250 - 299 4 138 76176

  • Find the total of \((Md - Mn)^2\) x Frequency, 292800.

  • Find the total Frequency, 50.

  • Compute the variance, \(S^2 = \frac{292800}{50 - 1}\) = 5975.5102

  • Compute the Standard Deviation, S = \(\sqrt{5975.5102}\) = 77.3014

ALEKS Resources

ALEKS Calculator


Below, you find a brief description and use of all functions available in the ALEKS Calculator that you are going to use during this semester.

\(\sum x\): Add all numeric data values (total).

  • For example, 2 + 3 + 7 + 1 = 13

  • In ALEKS: sum(2, 3, 7, 1)

\(\sum x^2\): Add the square of all numeric data values.

  • For example, \(2^2 + 3^2 + 7^2 + 1^2 = 63\)

  • In ALEKS: sumsq(2, 3, 7, 1)

\(\bar{X}\): Compute the sample mean. \(\bar{X}\) is read as X-bar.

  • For example, (2 + 3 + 7 + 1)/4 = 3.25

  • In ALEKS, mean(2, 3, 7, 1)

  • \(\bar{X} = \frac{1}{n}\sum x\)

  • \(\sum x = n \bar{X}\)

\(S_x\): Compute the sample standard deviation.

  • For example, \(\sqrt{\frac{(2 - 3.25)^2 + (3 - 3.25)^2 + (7 - 3.25)^2 + (1 - 3.25)^2}{4 - 1}} = 2.6299556397\)

  • In ALEKS, stdev(2, 3, 7, 1)

  • S = \(\sqrt{S^2}\)

  • \(S^2\) is known as the sample variance.

  • By definition, \(S^2\) = \(\frac{1}{n - 1}\sum(x_i - \bar{X})^2\)

  • \(\sum(x_i - \bar{X})^2\) = \((n - 1)S^2\)

  • There is also the population variance, \(\sigma^2\). The \(\sigma\) is read as sigma.

  • By definition, \(\sigma^2\) = \(\frac{1}{n}\sum(x_i - \bar{X})^2\) = \(\frac{n - 1}{n}S^2\)

  • Before using these formulas, check if your data set represents a sample or population.

Sort: Sort numeric data values in ascending order.

  • For example, order 2, 3, 7, 1 to 1, 2, 3, 7

[],[],: Add blank spaces to enter data values.

(: Open parenthesis. Useful when combining mathematical operations of defining data set.

): Close parenthesis. Useful when combining mathematical operations of defining data set.

\(\sqrt{x}\): Compute the square root of a non-negative number.

  • For example, \(\sqrt{9}\) = 3

n!: Compute the factorial of a whole number.

  • For example, 5! = 120

  • 5! is read as 5 factorial. 5! = 1 x 2 x 3 x 4 x 5

log: Compute the logarithm in base 10 of a number greater than 0.

  • For example, log(3) = 0.47712125472

ln: Compute the natural logarithm of a number greater than 0.

  • For example, ln(3) = 1.0986122887

\(_nP_r\): Compute a permutation. Total number of ordered selections of r units from n.

  • For example, \(_5P_2\) = \(\frac{5!}{(5 - 2)!}\) = 20

\(_nC_r\): Compute the combination. Total number of selections of r units from n. The order is NOT important. The symbol \(_nC_r\) is read as n choose r.

  • For example, \(_5C_2\) = \(\frac{5!}{2!(5 - 2)!}\) = 10

\(10^x\): Compute 10 to the x power.

  • For example, \(10^3\) = 1000

\(e^x\): Compute e to the x power.

  • For example, \(e^3\) = 20.085536923

Z: Compute the Z value corresponding to the right tail area in the Standard Normal Distribution.

  • For example, \(Z_{0.025}\) = 1.9599639822

t: Compute the T value corresponding to the right tail area in the T Distribution with k degrees of freedom.

  • For example, \(t_{0.025, df=8}\) = 2.3060041108

\(X^2\): Compute the \(X^2\) value corresponding to the right tail area in the Chi-Squared Distribution with k degrees of freedom.

  • For example, \(X^2_{0.025, df=8}\) = 17.53454614

F: Compute the F value corresponding to the right tail area in the F Distribution with k and l degrees of freedom.

  • For example, \(F_{0.025, df1=8, df2=5}\) = 6.7571720076

P(Z < []): Compute area to the left of a Z value in the Standard Normal Distribution.

  • For example, \(P(Z \leq 1.5)\) = 0.93319279873

P(t > []): Compute area to the right of a T value in the T Distribution with k degrees of freedom.

  • For example, P(T > 1.5, df=8) = 0.086001645976

\(P(X^2\) > []): Compute area to the right of a \(X^2\) value in the Chi-Squared Distribution with k degrees of freedom.

  • For example, \(P(X^2 > 10.5, df=8)\) = 0.23166973811

P(F > []): Compute area to the right of a F value in the F Distribution with k and l degrees of freedom.

  • For example, P(F > 10.5, df1=8, df2=5) = 0.0095561813

P(B_,_ \(\leq\) []): Compute the total probability of values at or below specific number in the binomial distribution with parameters n and p.

  • For example, \(P(B_{10},_{0.65} \leq 7)\) = 0.73839260862

  • \(P(B_{10},_{0.65} \leq 7)\) = p(0) + p(1) + p(2) + . + p(7)

\(x^y\): Raise x to the y power.

  • For example, \(2^5\) = 32

\(\pm\): Assign symbol positive of negative to a number.

\(\pi\): Pi number, 3.1415926536
